data.title: Why Brittany Murphy's friends say they are GLAD her British husband Simon Monjack is dead too
data.meta_description: Pneumonia was the primary cause of her death, with contributing factors of iron deficiency anaemia and 'multiple drug intoxication,' according to the Los Angeles County coroner's office.
data.text:
Simon Monjack is suitably sombre-looking as he opens the door to the cosmetic-strewn room where his wife, the actress Brittany Murphy, died last December after collapsing in the shower, suffering from pneumonia and with a cocktail of drugs in her skeletal body.

‘This,’ he says, ‘is the infamous bathroom. Obviously, no one has been in here to clean up yet’.

Pointing to a miniature chaise longue for dogs (this is LA, don’t forget), he continues: ‘This is the little doggy couch where she actually fell. When the paramedics came in, they pulled her through into the main room.’

Then, speaking directly into the camera belonging to the online gossip website who are videoing Monjack’s ghoulish tour, he adds: ‘You are the first people to see the infamous bathroom.’

Earlier this week — just two months after filming the poor-taste video for which he allegedly received around £10,000 — Monjack was found dead in the same bedroom where his tragic wife spent her last minutes.

Brittany Murphy was the talented, quirky actress from Atlanta, Georgia, who captured Hollywood’s attention with her scene-stealing performance in the 1995 comedy Clueless, about a group of spoilt American schoolgirls.

She was tipped for great things before she fell victim to the dark side of Hollywood, becoming hooked on prescription drugs and growing painfully thin due to her eating disorders.

Although it is too early for a post mortem, it is believed that Monjack died of heart failure. Like his wife, who died five months before, he was surrounded by bottles and bottles of prescription drugs.

His devastated mother Linda claims he died of a ‘broken heart’, while Brittany’s mother Sharon — who discovered both bodies — is said to be inconsolable.

But British-born Monjack, who was 40, leaves behind very few other people who are genuinely shocked or even saddened by his untimely demise.

‘People always say it’s a tragedy when someone dies, but in this case it’s more of a blessing,’ says Eric Ziegenbein, a former friend of Brittany.

‘Simon wanted to die. He struggled with depression for much of his life, and he felt like Brittany was the only thing he had to live for.

‘He was a full-blown drug addict by the time they were married, with not many prospects, and when she died he felt he had no reason for living.

‘Their relationship was so destructive it was like they were both waiting to die and just poisoning themselves. It got more and more dysfunctional, until it finally killed Brittany.

‘They were both zombies anyway. It’s not like they had any quality of life left. Sometimes death is a blessing for people who are suffering, and they were both suffering.’

Meanwhile, Brittany’s half brother, Tony Bertolotti, says he was not troubled by the death of the man who ‘helped kill my sister’.

‘The guy was insane,’ he continues. ‘He tried to keep my father’s name off her death certificate. That’s two people that have died living in that house within six months.

'When are people going to open their eyes about what was going on there?

‘My dad and I feel the same way; we are sad for my sister but not for him.’

An actress former friend of Brittany, who asked not to be named, says: ‘It’s sad that Simon died at the age of 40, but anyone who knew him — and especially the effect he had on Brittany — is not sad for the loss. He basically destroyed that girl.’

The name Simon Monjack was not well known at all before Brittany’s untimely death last year. But after she died, the man who was nicknamed ‘Conjack’ became hard to avoid — but for all the wrong reasons.

Monjack already had a reputation as a crook when he met Brittany in 2006 at a party in LA. He owed Coutts bank £400,000, had several other large debts, and had been accused of credit card fraud. One London woman lost £200,000 investing in one of his many disastrous ‘film’ projects.

He may have met a squalid end but Monjack had a good start in life. Born in Hillingdon, North London, to well-off Jewish parents (his mother ran her own interior design company while his dad worked in the City), he won a place at the local grammar school and was a popular pupil there.

Scene: An aerial view of Murphy's home in the hills of West Hollywood

Those that know him believe his life began to unravel following the death of his father from a brain tumour 15 years ago.

He had been married once before, to GMTV relationship therapist Simone Bienne, who told friends she was ‘mentally and physically assaulted’ by her husband. The marriage lasted just five months, ending in 2001.

Monjack then decided to move to LA to attempt to break into the film business, even though he had no experience or contacts in that area.

When his shady background emerged after Brittany’s death most people, surely, would have chosen to lie low, particularly having lost a loved one.

But Monjack appeared to revel in the attention, becoming a fixture on the chat show circuit, where he talked of his love for Brittany and insisted on his innocence of any blame for her demise.

And right up until her post mortem revealed the level of her drug use, he maintained that the only drugs Brittany took were for her heart murmer and vitamins.

But then a lot of what Monjack said turned out to be, well, less than true.

Brittany was fired from her last film, The Caller, because a drunk Monjack was getting in the way of production

Keen to pin the blame on everyone, anyone (but himself), at one point he said he was planning to sue Warner Brothers for killing his wife because they cancelled a contract for her to appear on Happy Feet 2 — the sequel to the highly successful animated penguin film.

Not true, said the company: ‘Warner Bros and Ms Murphy never entered into any deal for Happy Feet 2, and thus there was no contract to cancel.’

Another time he insisted ‘Hollywood killed her’ because they were no longer giving her jobs. But many of those in the know said the only reason she had trouble keeping work — she always had offers — was because of Monjack.

‘He started telling her what film roles to take, and within two years she went from being an A-lister to a C-lister,’ says an actress friend who starred with her in Sin City.

‘She stopped taking calls from her agents and managers, and let Simon take complete control of her personally and professionally — with disastrous consequences.’

Just a month before her death, Brittany was fired from her last film, The Caller, because a drunk Monjack was getting in the way of production, and she refused to tell him to leave.

While calling himself a ‘producer’, ‘screenwriter’ and ‘director’, he had only one failed movie to his name.

And while he insisted to all and sundry that he was extremely wealthy (earlier this year he boasted: ‘I spent over a million on her engagement rings, probably $3 million on clothes — that was all me’), the truth was that until he met Brittany, he was in debt up to his eyeballs.

Fitting: Monjack was buried next to his wife Brittany Murphy at Forest Lawn Memorial Park in the Hollywood Hills

Shortly after Brittany’s death, he set up the Brittany Murphy Foundation, which he said was a charity to fund arts education for underprivileged children. He said he was donating $1 million of his own money, and announced a ball with tickets going at $1,000 a pop.

But just a few days later it was revealed that he had never applied for charity status; meaning, in effect, that he could have done what he liked with the money.

In a statement, the Brittany Murphy Foundation said it was simply an oversight: ‘In an effort to get the foundation off the ground quickly, we established it as a private foundation, with plans to apply for non-profit status down the road.’

It is unclear whether Monjack was a compulsive liar or just intent on impressing people, but he had also claimed to have bought Brittany her £4 million Hollywood Hills home. But her will showed that she owned it all herself; and she had left it to her mother Sharon.

Within two months of Brittany’s death, Sharon had put it on the market, before rapidly taking it off again as she hated the way people who were not genuine buyers were using its sale as a means to get a macabre tour of her daughter’s life.

That did not appear to stop Monjack, though, who gave several viewings of the house to his new journalist friends. He became closest to Radaronline reporter Amber Goodhand, who filmed the bathroom where his wife died.

‘Sure, I wondered about his intentions, but I just thought he was a narcissist — like everyone else in Hollywood,’ she says.

‘She was obviously very troubled to get involved with him in the first place, but Simon was her “bottom”'

‘He wasn’t at all what I was expecting. He had such a shady reputation, but I thought he was nice. He was very intelligent and charming.

‘Brittany’s death took a real toll on him — whatever people say, he loved her. He had put on about 40lb and spent most of his time holed up in the house with Sharon.

‘I never noticed him taking any drugs, although he had told me he was unwell. He said he would not tell me any more as he did not want to detract from Brittany.’

While not quite an A-lister, Brittany Murphy was a well-known face about town and had dated a number of top actors, including Demi Moore’s husband Ashton Kutcher, and her bubbly personality meant she had lots of friends.

However, she was already experimenting with drugs and having problems with destructive relationships and depression before her marriage. Monjack only made things worse.

‘She was obviously very troubled to get involved with him in the first place, but Simon was her “bottom”,’ says the actress friend. ‘Prior to Simon, Brittany was a little crazy — but she was still functional.

‘When she and Simon hooked up, it was a rapid downward spiral. Her friends saw the warning signs within two months, but as soon as anyone expressed concern, she would just shut them out.

'Finally, she got so isolated it was basically just her and him — which was exactly how he wanted it.

‘Brittany was thin before she met him, and she’d had eating issues all her adult life, but they really escalated after she met Simon. She basically stopped eating.

'She was just popping pills and drinking. She got her nutrition from whatever juice she mixed her vodka with.

‘Everyone warned Brittany that Simon was just using her because she was famous, and to break into Hollywood — but she didn’t see it.’

‘Simon and Brittany basically were playing pharmacy in their house. They had pills to make them happy, pills to make them sleep, pills to give them energy.’

Wasted talent: Brittany Murphy was once one of Hollywood's most sought after actresses

Brittany’s death should have been a lesson, but the actress says that it only made things worse for Monjack.

‘He started sleeping 19 hours a day, and eating in bed. He didn’t shower for a week at a time.

‘I think he wanted to die. He kept taking more and more pain pills, hoping he wouldn’t wake up. He felt so guilty he wanted to punish himself. Well, half of him wanted to punish himself, and the other half wanted to join Brittany.

‘It’s sad. He destroyed her, and he destroyed himself.’

Ironically, shortly before his death, Monjack had talked about pulling himself together.

He had experienced breathing problems on a plane shortly before Brittany died, which he had attributed variously to asthma and heart problems, and he knew he had to sort himself out.

‘He said he was going to lose the excess weight,’ says Amber Goodhand.

He also had a myriad of ambitious career plans. First off was to relaunch the Brittany Murphy Foundation — this time, with the relevant paperwork.

Roger Neal, his former publicist, says Monjack had even put off heart surgery, which he knew he needed, because he wanted to get the foundation off the ground first.

‘He had so much to live for, so much going for him — he was a very busy guy,’ he says. ‘He put himself to the side because he wanted to fulfil that part of the legacy for Brittany.

He said to me: “I’ll be fine. Just let me get past this gala, and I’ll be fine.” ’

He was also planning to move — variously to New York or Europe, depending on which interview you read — with Brittany’s mother Sharon, who had inherited all of her daughter’s estate.

The pair, who remained together in Brittany’s house, had become so close, calling each other ‘sweetheart’ and ‘darling’, that there were even rumours of a romance. That was vigorously denied; it seems more that they were clinging to each other with their grief.

Another project Monjack was planning was to photograph ballerinas around the world, as Brittany had loved dance.

Meanwhile, his mother says he was ‘about to direct an opera in Los Angeles’.

It is hard to know what is really true, outside of the fact that two people, who clearly had enough talent and luck to lead happy lives, are dead before their time.

Victims of Hollywood? No, not really. They were addicts who were victims of their own demons.
